Monitoring Proxmox with Prometheus + Grafana - Kyle Wilson 1/2/26

Monitoring VM
1. Create Ubuntu Server VM on Proxmox (2GB+ RAM recommended)
2. Update system
3. Install Prometheus
4. Start and enable Prometheus service
5. Verify Prometheus is running
6. Install Grafana
7. Start and enable Grafana service
8. Verify Grafana web interface

Proxmox Host
1. Install Node Exporter
2. Verify Node Exporter service

Prometheus Configuration
1. Edit prometheus.yml
2. Add scrape target for Proxmox host
3. Restart Prometheus
4. Verify target appears in Prometheus

Grafana Configuration
1. Add Prometheus data source
2. Import dashboard
3. (Optional) Enable anonymous access


------------------------------------------------------------

MONITORING VM SETUP (Ubuntu Server)

Always:
	sudo apt update
	sudo apt upgrade -y


------------------------------------------------------------

INSTALL PROMETHEUS

Install Prometheus:
	sudo apt install prometheus -y

Enable and start Prometheus:
	sudo systemctl enable prometheus
	sudo systemctl start prometheus

Verify:
	sudo systemctl status prometheus

Should show: active (running)

Test via browser:
	http://<monitoring-vm-ip>:9090


------------------------------------------------------------

INSTALL GRAFANA

Install dependencies:
	sudo apt install -y apt-transport-https software-properties-common

Create keyring directory:
	sudo mkdir -p /etc/apt/keyrings/

Add Grafana repository key:
	wget -q -O - https://packages.grafana.com/gpg.key | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/grafana.gpg

Add repository:
	echo "deb [signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/grafana.gpg] https://packages.grafana.com/oss/deb stable main" | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/grafana.list

Update packages:
	sudo apt update

Install Grafana:
	sudo apt install grafana -y

Enable and start Grafana:
	sudo systemctl enable --now grafana-server

Test via browser:
	http://<monitoring-vm-ip>:3000

Default credentials:
	admin / admin


------------------------------------------------------------

NODE EXPORTER ON PROXMOX HOST

SSH into the host you want to monitor.

Update system:
	apt update

Install Node Exporter:
	apt install prometheus-node-exporter -y

Node Exporter runs automatically on port 9100.

Verify:
	sudo systemctl status prometheus-node-exporter


------------------------------------------------------------

CONFIGURE PROMETHEUS SCRAPE TARGET

Edit Prometheus configuration file:
	sudo nano /etc/prometheus/prometheus.yml

Replace the scrape_configs section with:

	scrape_configs:

	  - job_name: 'prometheus'
	    static_configs:
	      - targets: ['localhost:9090']

	  - job_name: 'Anything You’d Like'
	    static_configs:
	      - targets: ['Host IP']
	        labels:
	          nodename: 'Anything You’d Like'

Replace "Host IP" with the Proxmox host LAN IP.

Restart Prometheus:
	sudo systemctl restart prometheus

Verify the host is visible:
	http://<monitoring-vm-ip>:9090/targets


------------------------------------------------------------

CONFIGURE GRAFANA DATA SOURCE

Open Grafana:
	http://<monitoring-vm-ip>:3000

Navigate to:
	Connections → Add Data Source → Prometheus

Set URL:
	http://localhost:9090

Click:
	Save & Test


------------------------------------------------------------

IMPORT READY-MADE DASHBOARD

Navigate to:
	Dashboards → New → Import

Enter dashboard ID:
	1860

Click:
	Load

Choose your Prometheus data source.

Click:
	Import

You will now see dashboards showing:
	CPU usage
	Memory usage
	Network traffic
	Disk metrics

Example metric query:
	(irate(node_cpu_seconds_total{mode="idle"}[5m])) * 100


------------------------------------------------------------

OPTIONAL: ENABLE ANONYMOUS GRAFANA ACCESS (LOCAL ONLY)

Find the Grafana config file:
	sudo journalctl -u grafana-server -b | grep -i "Config" -m1

Edit the configuration file:
	sudo nano <grafana-config-file>

Uncomment and set:

	[auth.anonymous]
	enabled = true
	org_name = Main Org.
	org_role = Viewer

	[auth]
	disable_login_form = true

Restart Grafana:
	sudo systemctl restart grafana-server


Now Grafana can be accessed directly via:
	http://<monitoring-vm-ip>:3000


------------------------------------------------------------

Done — Prometheus is now collecting metrics and Grafana is visualizing them for your Proxmox host.
